<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n14030c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14030c">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14030c"> 30(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Heartburn / (Herzeleide) ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A similarly profound meaning pervades the German epic of &ldquo;Parsival&rdquo; in which Wolfram von Eschenbach (1200) attempted the Germanization of Christianity. The evident sense of conviction permeating this deep mystery causes it to glow with a radiant and poetic fervour. In this poem it is the <i>German</i> who is the &ldquo;pure fool&rdquo;: a knightly hero, who, like Siegfried, guileless and eager for action, sets forth to seek his match in single combat <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> in order to slay &ldquo;the faithless one,&rdquo; the &ldquo;Host of Hell&rdquo; (Satan), whom his mother, <mark>Herzloide</mark>, so fears, to the end that he may find <i>God</i>, Who, &ldquo;purer than the day, had once borne a human countenance.&rdquo; <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Mother of Parsifal in Wagner&apos;s opera. </mm> </dd></dl>
